The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Grasim profit jumps 26%

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, April 29: Aditya Birla group flagship company Grasim Industries has posted a 26 per cent increase in net profit for the year ended March 31, 2005 at Rs 978 crore compared with Rs 779.30 crore for the previous fiscal.

 The net profit includes Rs 92 crore by way of diminution in the value of investment of its subsidiary Digvijay Cements.

 Net profit for the fourth quarter after total tax expenses was up 14 per cent at Rs 322 crore compared with Rs 282.10 crore in the corresponding quarter previous fiscal.

 Its turnover at Rs 1642 crore was higher by 6 per cent. Capacity utilisation, strengthening of operational efficiencies and marketing of higher volumes of an enriched product mix have been key to the growth.

 The company?s profit after tax, even after the charge for diminution, has risen by 14 per cent.

 The board has recommended a dividend of 160 per cent for the current fiscal compared with 140 per cent last year, which will amount in a total outgo of Rs 167.20 crore, including a corporate tax on dividend at the rate of 14.02 per cent.

 The viscose staple fibre business surged with production at 247,952 tonnes, 12 per cent higher over that of the previous year. Sales volumes were only marginally higher due to the increased availability of cotton during the year. Realisations grew by 9 per cent at Rs 79,008 per tonne, in line with the international trend, leading to higher operating profits.

 During the fiscal, the capacity utilisation of the sponge iron business of Grasim touched an all-time high of 87 per cent while realisations in the segment increased 39 per cent to Rs 2,774 per MT. 

 Zee net up 

 Zee Telefilms Ltd has posted a 7.7 per cent rise in consolidated net profit at Rs 3,175 crore for the fiscal ended March 31, 2005 compared with Rs 2,948 crore in the previous fiscal.

 Operating revenues was Rs 13,954 crore compared with Rs 12,640 crore in the previous fiscal.

 Bank of India earnings plunge

 Bank of India has posted a sharp drop in its net profit at Rs 340.05 crore in 2004-05 compared with Rs 1,008.32 crore in 2003-04.

 The board has declared a final dividend of 10 per cent, taking the total dividend outgo to 20 per cent for 2004-05, chairman and managing director M. Venugopalan said.




